    PAID FOR AND POSTED BY

    On paper, Adewunmi Roye
    Okupe’s life read like a
    blueprint for the American Dream.

    On paper, Adewunmi Roye Okupe’s life read like a
    blueprint for the American Dream.

    Born in Lagos, Nigeria, Okupe, who goes by Roye, moved to the United States at 17 to attend college. He eventually earned a master’s degree in computer science and took a job as a web developer. “My salary literally doubled in three years,” he says. Okupe was a success by almost any measure of the word. But no matter how much money he made, he still felt unfulfilled. Okupe couldn’t stop dreaming about superheroes.

    An “aha moment” is often described as a sudden insight or epiphany that radically changes a person’s perspective. It can be a decision-making moment, spiritual realization or creative breakthrough. Something clicks in the brain and — pop! — things just seem to fall into place.

    Graphic novelist Roye Okupe visits his favorite comic shop, Maryland’s Alliance Comics. Photography by Stephen Voss
    Realizing an Aha Moment
    Meditation and mindfulness-based cognitive therapy can help people realize an aha moment. So can taking a relaxing vacation away from everyday stresses and habits.

    Growing up in Lagos, Okupe fell in love with cartoons like “Teenage Mutant Ninja Turtles” and “Transformers,” and superheroes including Batman, Superman and Spider-Man. “I’ve been a total nerd ever since then,” says Okupe, whose passion only increased with the first wave of the Hollywood superhero boom. But even though more African-American superheroes were slowly becoming mainstream, the characters didn’t reflect Okupe’s own experience. “If you’re not a hardcore comic book and superhero fan, you probably cannot name five superheroes that you know that were born in Africa,” he says.

    Since 2008, Okupe had been quietly developing a mental image of his own superhero — the Nigerian-born Wale Williams — who would defend his home of Lagoon City from the forces of evil. After taking stock of his situation, and seeing other independent comic book writers succeed, everything came into focus. ”I saw other people doing it and I believed in myself,” Okupe says. “I decided I had to take the risk, quit my job and follow a passion that I’ve had all my life.”

    Okupe invented Wale Williams when he noticed other superheroes lives didn’t reflect his own experience. Photography by Stephen Voss

    Dr. Kyra Bobinet is a University of California, San Francisco and Harvard Public Health graduate who teaches neuroscience and health engagement design at the Stanford School of Medicine. Bobinet also runs a design firm called engagedIN that focuses on engaging people in well-being and behavior change. “My whole passion is why we don’t do what we know we should do, and designing for the disparity between those two aspects of our brain,” says Bobinet.

    According to Bobinet, an aha moment like Okupe’s is actually the result of many individual thoughts, conscious or unconscious, that accumulate over time. “Every time I have the thought, ‘oh, I should do this’ or ‘I want to be that’ it throws a penny in the jar of my implicit memory,” she says. The struggle between what people want to do versus what they actually do can result in “cognitive dissonance,” which they may not be consciously aware of. After building up as patterns in someone’s implicit memory, a realization can occur.

    Tito Beveridge turned a hobby he loved into award-winning vodka Tito’s Handmade Vodka. Photography provided by Tito’s Handmade Vodka
    A Lifetime of Epiphanies
    Aha moments can feel like they happen in an instant, but these epiphanies usually come from a lifetime of consciously (or unconsciously) considering various options.

    Beveridge had worked numerous oil jobs in his home state, starting as a roughneck on a rig when he was just 18. After setting his dreams on becoming a Texas oilman, Beveridge earned degrees in geology and geophysics from the University of Texas. He then cruised through a laundry list of jobs including, but not limited to: petroleum geologist (“got laid off”), oil company owner (“went broke when oil hit six dollars”), seismic data processor (“quit”) and drilling company owner (“oil went down again and I went broke again”). As Beveridge puts it, “I loved the oil business and it did not love me back.”

    Step

    1

    Aha moments can be anything from making a breakthrough at work, to discovering your true passion. The following are some of the processes the brain goes through to reach an aha moment.
    Though it may seem that way, aha moments don’t arrive out of the blue. A dissatisfied person may accumulate hopes, dreams and possibilities as implicit memories for years.
    Some experts believe mindfulness meditation techniques can help the brain free itself from some inhibitions and reach an aha moment that’s just below the surface.
    Scientists suggest aha moments can arise from a lessening of activity in the brain’s prefrontal cortex, which manages inhibition. Aha moments are also paired with increased activity in the right temporal lobe, which reflects creative function.
    If the right conditions occur in the brain, an aha moment could be imminent.
    After reaching an aha moment, it’s important to think it through logically: Is your new passion feasible? Do you have the skills and determination to follow through?
    If the answer is yes, it’s time to pursue your passion. Your brain has reached its aha moment!

    After winding up back in Austin and becoming a mortgage broker in the early ‘90s, Beveridge still wasn’t satisfied. But he did have a hobby. “I had been making vodka infusions for friends for Christmas presents and strangers started calling me the vodka guy and telling me I should start selling my vodka infusions,” says Beveridge. “A guy on TV was talking about discovering your passion by listing what you love to do and what you are good at, then you wrap a job around it. I suddenly realized I had a passion for making liquor.” By 1997, Tito’s Handmade Vodka was up and running as a commercial operation.

    Someone experiencing an aha moment can feel jolted, like they’ve been hit by a flash of lightning. But that’s not the case, at least from a neurological perspective. According to Dr. James Giordano, a professor of neurology at Georgetown University Medical, big decisions — even those precipitated by aha moments — can be years in the making. “A lot of the information that we’re beginning to acquire about [emotional and rational decision-making] is coming from this relatively new field called neuroeconomics,” he says. “We’re looking at the neurological and cognitive processes that are involved in decision making and how individuals will use various resources and services to make life decisions that affect their behaviors and their outcomes.”

    Beveridge urges people to find the intersection between what they like to do and what they’re good at. Photography provided by Tito’s Handmade Vodka

    Giordano says decisions stem from a cost benefit analysis where we weigh thoughts, emotions and behavioral pros and cons. An aha moment, according to Giordano, happens when a person shifts from perceiving a big life change as something more necessary than scary. “When we’re looking at the things we’re doing on a daily basis and it becomes so negatively balanced for us, the possibility of making something that is a major life change — and in some cases, may be a little anxiety-provoking or may be dramatically and diametrically different than what we’ve been doing all along — carries with it such expectational, positive emotion, that it compels us to act.”

    Realizing an Aha Moment
    Meditation and mindfulness-based cognitive therapy can help people realize an aha moment. So can taking a relaxing vacation away from everyday stresses and habits.
    A LIFETIME OF CONSIDERATION
    Aha moments can feel as if they happen in an instant, but these epiphanies usually come from a lifetime of consciously (or unconsciously) considering various options.
    New Possibilities
    People of sound mind can have aha moments whether they’ve been successful in other pursuits or not. New possibilities can always be realized.

    Erin Gavle’s journey to Eldorado started in New York. “I call it my past life,” she says, with a laugh. “I was on the creative side of advertising, working as an associate creative director. I thought it was going to be my lifelong career – It was something I couldn’t fathom not doing.”

    Until, of course, she could. Faced with long hours at the office and a growing realization that she wasn’t spending enough time doing the things she cared about, Gavle decided she needed a change. “I was going to move to L.A., make some jewelry, sit on the beach, do some meditation and some yoga, figure it all out and jump back into advertising,” she says.

    Erin Gavle left a lucrative advertising career to found a vintage general store in her home city of Detroit. Photography by Sean Proctor

    For others looking to find their own aha moment, Bobinet suggests practicing mindfulness, like the yoga and meditation mentioned by Gavle, could free them from the brain’s more inhibitive functions. According to Bobinet, the prefrontal cortex is a part of the brain’s frontal lobe that keeps us in check. “It keeps us from saying the wrong things,” she says. “It’s the area where we’re most self-conscious.”

    Bobinet also says that aha moments are often paired with an increase in activity on the brain’s right temporal lobe, which lights up during creative activity. “This area, called the anterior cingulate, opens your vista of what you consider to be a possible solution,” says Bobinet. “As it is stimulated, you start to consider things that are unusual solutions or may be normally dominated by your realities, your biases or your prejudices.”

    After moving to L.A., Gavle returned home for a wedding in Detroit, still unsure of her next step. “I was staying in the bedroom that I had grown up in, and I had found this piece of paper I had probably written when I was in high school,” says Gavle. “It was a life to-do list. At the bottom of the list, it said ‘open a boutique by the time I’m 40.’ It was kind of like this message from the universe.” Gavle’s anterior cingulate was firing full-blast.

    Gavle sells wares she collects from her travels around the world. Photography by Sean Proctor
    She loves it when people find meaning in objects that also called out to her. Photography by Sean Proctor
    “It represents a happiness moment,” she says. “And then I get to share that with somebody else.” Photography by Sean Proctor
    The stores stocks everything from jewelry, to clothing, to all manner of trinkets. Photography by Sean Proctor
    “Eldorado is like taking a trip down memory lane,” she says. Photography by Sean Proctor
    1/5
    New Possibilities
    People of sound mind can have aha moments whether they’ve been successful in other pursuits or not. New possibilities can always be realized.

    Though Okupe, Beveridge and Gavle all arrived at aha moments in different ways, they all shared the willpower necessary to deviate from safe career paths to pursue uncertain ambitions. “Very often, we see the grass being greener on the other side,” says Giordano, who urges anyone with an aha moment to carefully consider his or her options. “An ounce of preparation is probably worth pounds and pounds of cure.”

    After her initial realization, Gavle started making plans to move back to her home city to open what would become Eldorado General Store, a vintage shop in the heart of Detroit that sells items Gavle collects on her travels around the world. “Sometimes it’s easier to figure out what you don’t want to do before you figure out what you want to do,” says Gavle. “Eldorado, to me, was about creating a lifestyle. It was about redefining what happiness means to me.”

    As it turns out, the gamble paid off for all three entrepreneurs and they now hope to inspire others to make similar leaps of faith. Okupe is set to release the second volume of "E.X.O. - The Legend of Wale Williams" later this year and wants to show other writers that it’s possible to follow in his footsteps. “There’s a lot of people that are so scared, a lot of people that are very nervous about taking a chance on themselves,” he says. “I know this because I was there as well. I’m pretty much just a regular guy who decided to take a chance on himself.”

    Beveridge, who has won numerous awards for Tito’s Handmade Vodka, now advises others on finding the right intersection between their passions and skill-sets with an initiative called Fresh Start. “If you fail, it may feel as if you are going to die but you won't and you don't,” he says. “Brush yourself off and make another passion list. These failures become the foundation for your ultimate success, but only if you keep trying.”

    Meanwhile, Gavle is living happily in Detroit where she’s been able to give other artisans in her growing community a platform to show their wares. ”That’s why I named it Eldorado General Store, because ‘general store’ is about that sense of community,” says Gavle. “It’s about pushing creativity further and allowing people’s passions to spark and grow.”

    Tito's All-Time Favorite Recipe

    Ingredients:

    1 1/2 oz Tito's Handmade Vodka

    4 oz sparkling mineral water

    Slice of orange

    Slice of lime

    Method

    Combine Tito's Handmade Vodka and mineral water in a rocks glass with ice. Stir and garnish.

    Garnish

    Orange and lime slices

    Glass

    Rocks glass
